import React, { useState } from 'react';
import PageTemplate from '../components/PageTemplate';
import heroImage from '../images/ai-menu/1.png';
import screenshot1 from '../images/ai-menu/1.png';
import screenshot2 from '../images/ai-menu/2.png';
import screenshot3 from '../images/ai-menu/3.png';
import screenshot4 from '../images/ai-menu/4.png';
import architectureDiagram from '../images/ai-menu/architecture.png';

export default function AIMenuPage() {
  const [carouselIdx, setCarouselIdx] = useState(0);
  return (
    <PageTemplate
      title="AI Sandwich Kiosk on Edge Hardware: Local LLM on RubikPi3"
      image={heroImage}
      metadata={[
        { label: 'Role', value: 'Full-Stack AI Engineer' },
        { label: 'Stack', value: 'React, FastAPI, Ollama, Qwen3, RubikPi3' },
        { label: 'Context', value: 'Qualcomm internship, client-facing demo' },
        { label: 'Outcome', value: 'Fully offline LLM kiosk on edge hardware' }
      ]}
    >
      <p>
        As part of my internship at Qualcomm, I built a self-service sandwich kiosk that runs a local large language model directly on a RubikPi3 single-board computer. The goal was to create a compelling, hands-on demonstration of Edge AI capabilities for clients visiting the Qualcomm office, something tangible they could interact with, not a slide deck.
      </p>
      <p>
        You walk up to the kiosk, describe what you feel like eating (or what you can't eat), and the AI figures out your sandwich, all without a single cloud API call. The entire inference stack runs on the board sitting in front of you.
      </p>

      <h2>The Problem: Making Edge AI Tangible</h2>
      <p>
        "AI at the edge" is a compelling pitch, but it's hard to demonstrate in a way that's immediately intuitive to non-technical audiences. A benchmark chart doesn't convey latency, interactivity, or the practical feel of running a model locally. A kiosk does.
      </p>
      <p>
        The sandwich shop context is intentional: it's a constrained domain with a finite menu, which makes it realistic for testing whether a small on-device model can reliably extract structured data from open-ended natural language without hallucinating ingredients that don't exist. It's also immediately relatable to any visitor who has ever ordered food.
      </p>

      <h2>Hardware: RubikPi3</h2>
      <p>
        The RubikPi3 is a Qualcomm-powered edge AI development board with a dedicated NPU for on-device inference. The entire backend (LLM runtime, API server, everything) runs on this board. The frontend is a browser-based kiosk UI that points at the board's local IP. No internet connection required at any point during operation.
      </p>

      <h2>System Architecture</h2>
      <p>
        The data flow is entirely local. Nothing leaves the board:
      </p>
      <div style={{margin: '24px 0', textAlign: 'center'}}>
        <img src={architectureDiagram} alt="AI Sandwich Kiosk system architecture diagram" style={{maxWidth: '100%', height: 'auto', borderRadius: '8px', boxShadow: '0 4px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.1)'}} />
      </div>

      <h3>Backend</h3>
      <p>
        The backend is a <strong>FastAPI</strong> server exposing a single streaming endpoint: <code>GET /api/chat/stream</code>. It forwards the user's prompt to Ollama using the chat completions API with streaming enabled, then pipes the token stream back to the browser as Server-Sent Events (SSE).
      </p>
      <p>
        The model is <strong>Qwen3 1.7B</strong> in <code>q4_k_m</code> quantization, small enough to run at interactive speeds on the board and capable enough to follow complex structured instructions reliably.
      </p>
      <p>
        The most technically interesting backend piece is the <strong>recommendation parser</strong>, a streaming state machine that handles the structured output extraction:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>All text before a fixed XML-like opening delimiter is passed directly to the SSE token stream (what the user reads in the chat)</li>
        <li>Everything between the delimiters is buffered silently, never shown to the user</li>
        <li>After the stream ends, the buffered content is parsed and validated as JSON against the actual menu IDs</li>
        <li>A named SSE event (<code>event: recommendation</code>) carries the validated order to the frontend</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        This means the AI can hold a natural conversation (explaining ingredient combinations, asking about allergies, making suggestions) while simultaneously constructing a machine-readable order in the background. The user only sees the conversational text; the JSON is invisible.
      </p>
      <p>
        The validator is strict: any ingredient ID not in the predefined menu set is rejected, preventing hallucinations from propagating into the order.
      </p>

      <h3>Frontend</h3>
      <p>
        The UI is built with <strong>React 18 + Vite</strong> and organized into three screens, with state managed by <strong>Zustand</strong>:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>WelcomeScreen</strong>: a split layout with the AI chat panel on the right. Quick-select chips let users start a conversation with one tap. When the model emits a recommendation, a "Build my sandwich" button activates that applies the full order and advances to confirmation.</li>
        <li><strong>BuilderScreen</strong>: a seven-step manual wizard (bread → protein → veggies → sauces → extras → drink → summary) with the AI panel alongside. At any step, users can describe what they want to the AI and apply the resulting recommendation to jump ahead.</li>
        <li><strong>ConfirmScreen</strong>: final order review before submission.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The <code>useAIStream</code> hook encapsulates the full SSE lifecycle: opening the <code>EventSource</code>, accumulating tokens into the message list for real-time display, listening for the named recommendation event, and cleaning up on unmount. It also includes a mock mode (word-by-word timer) for developing the UI on a laptop without Ollama running.
      </p>

      <h2>The Customer Journey</h2>
      <p>
        The screenshots below show the complete user flow through the kiosk, from initial interaction to order confirmation.
      </p>

      {(() => {
        const slides = [
          {
            src: screenshot1,
            alt: 'AI assistant responding to a user query about sandwich preferences',
            caption: 'The AI assistant holding a natural conversation, asking about preferences, dietary restrictions, and making suggestions. The recommendation JSON is being constructed in the background, invisible to the user.',
          },
          {
            src: screenshot2,
            alt: 'Step-by-step sandwich builder: selecting bread',
            caption: 'The manual builder wizard alongside the AI panel. Users who prefer to choose each ingredient directly can do so step-by-step, while still having the AI available for advice at any point.',
          },
          {
            src: screenshot3,
            alt: 'Sandwich builder: ingredient selection mid-flow',
            caption: 'Mid-flow ingredient selection. Veggies, sauces, and extras are all multi-select; the AI recommendation can auto-fill all of them in one step.',
          },
          {
            src: screenshot4,
            alt: 'Order confirmation screen',
            caption: 'The confirmation screen showing the complete order before submission. Whether the user built it manually or let the AI do it, the final step is the same.',
          },
        ];
        const prev = () => setCarouselIdx(i => (i - 1 + slides.length) % slides.length);
        const next = () => setCarouselIdx(i => (i + 1) % slides.length);
        const btnStyle = {
          background: 'none',
          border: 'none',
          fontSize: '1.8em',
          cursor: 'pointer',
          padding: '0 16px',
          color: 'inherit',
          lineHeight: 1,
        };
        return (
          <div style={{margin: '30px 0', textAlign: 'center'}}>
            <div style={{display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', justifyContent: 'center'}}>
              <button onClick={prev} style={btnStyle} aria-label="Previous">&#8249;</button>
              <img
                src={slides[carouselIdx].src}
                alt={slides[carouselIdx].alt}
                style={{maxWidth: 'calc(100% - 80px)', height: 'auto', borderRadius: '8px', boxShadow: '0 4px 6px rgba(0,0,0,0.1)'}}
              />
              <button onClick={next} style={btnStyle} aria-label="Next">&#8250;</button>
            </div>
            <p style={{marginTop: '10px', fontStyle: 'italic', color: '#666', fontSize: '0.9em'}}>
              {slides[carouselIdx].caption}
            </p>
            <div style={{marginTop: '8px', display: 'flex', justifyContent: 'center', gap: '8px'}}>
              {slides.map((_, i) => (
                <button
                  key={i}
                  onClick={() => setCarouselIdx(i)}
                  aria-label={`Go to slide ${i + 1}`}
                  style={{
                    width: '8px', height: '8px', borderRadius: '50%', border: 'none',
                    background: i === carouselIdx ? '#555' : '#ccc',
                    cursor: 'pointer', padding: 0,
                  }}
                />
              ))}
            </div>
          </div>
        );
      })()}

      <h2>The Structured Output Problem</h2>
      <p>
        Getting reliable structured output from a 1.7B parameter model is the core engineering challenge. Approaches like JSON-mode or constrained decoding exist, but I favored a delimited-extraction pattern for its simplicity and debuggability:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The system prompt gives the model an explicit format template with filled-in examples using actual menu IDs</li>
        <li>The model is instructed to only use IDs from an enumerated list, no free-text ingredient names</li>
        <li>The backend validator rejects anything that doesn't match, so a bad response simply means no recommendation is auto-applied; the user can keep chatting</li>
        <li>A <code>ready</code> flag lets the model express uncertainty ("I don't have enough information yet") without forcing a premature recommendation</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        For a constrained menu domain like this, the approach works reliably. The model never needs to reason about open-ended ingredient space; it picks from a fixed list, which dramatically reduces the surface area for errors.
      </p>

      <h2>Dual-Mode Interface: AI and Manual Builder Coexisting</h2>
      <p>
        One design decision worth highlighting: both modes (the conversational AI and the step-by-step builder) are always available simultaneously. A user doesn't choose one path at the start and get locked in.
      </p>
      <p>
        This turned out to be more useful than a purely AI-first design. Visitors who are skeptical of AI ordering still have a full-featured manual path. Visitors who start with the AI can switch to manual at any step to fine-tune. And because the AI recommendation updates the same Zustand cart that the manual builder uses, switching between modes is seamless, with no state inconsistency.
      </p>

      <h2>Key Learnings</h2>
      <p>
        Running inference on edge hardware forces tradeoffs that cloud APIs abstract away completely. At 1.7B parameters with 4-bit quantization, you trade some reasoning depth for full offline operation, zero network latency, and no per-request cost. For a demo kiosk in a controlled domain, the tradeoff is clearly worth it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The streaming parser was the most technically interesting piece to build. The naive approach (emitting all tokens directly to the UI) causes the JSON blob to appear mid-stream in the chat window. Hiding it requires a stateful streaming parser that decides in real time which tokens to show and which to buffer, with the decision hinging on fixed delimiter strings. It's a small piece of infrastructure that makes the entire conversational experience feel clean.
      </p>
      <p>
        Finally, the project reinforced what makes a good technology demonstration: it's not a spec sheet, it's a task. Visitors don't need to understand NPUs or quantization to appreciate that they just ordered a sandwich by describing their allergies to a small computer on a table, with no internet connection.
      </p>

      <h2>Technology Stack</h2>
      <table style={{margin: '20px 0', borderCollapse: 'collapse', width: '100%'}}>
        <thead>
          <tr style={{borderBottom: '2px solid #333'}}>
            <th style={{padding: '10px', textAlign: 'left'}}>Layer</th>
            <th style={{padding: '10px', textAlign: 'left'}}>Technology</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {[
            ['Hardware', 'RubikPi3'],
            ['LLM Runtime', 'Ollama'],
            ['Model', 'Qwen3 1.7B q4_k_m'],
            ['Backend', 'FastAPI + Python (httpx for async streaming)'],
            ['Frontend', 'React 18 + Vite'],
            ['State Management', 'Zustand'],
            ['Styling', 'CSS Modules + CSS custom properties'],
            ['Transport', 'Server-Sent Events (native EventSource API)'],
          ].map(([layer, tech]) => (
            <tr key={layer} style={{borderBottom: '1px solid #ddd'}}>
              <td style={{padding: '10px', fontWeight: 'bold'}}>{layer}</td>
              <td style={{padding: '10px'}}>{tech}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </PageTemplate>
  );
}
